  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "While \"revert back\" is commonly used and understood, it's technically considered **redundant**. The word \"revert\" already means \"to return to a former state, condition, or practice.\" So, adding \"back\" is unnecessary.\n\nThink of it like saying \"ascend up\" or \"descend down\" - the \"up\" and \"down\" are already implied in \"ascend\" and \"descend.\"\n\n**Here's why it's considered redundant:**\n\n*   \"Revert\" inherently contains the idea of returning.\n\n**Examples:**\n\n*   **Correct:** \"The system will revert to its default settings.\"\n*   **Redundant:** \"The system will revert back to its default settings.\"\n\n**Why do people say it?**\n\n*   **Emphasis:** People often use \"revert back\" for emphasis, even though it's grammatically unnecessary.\n*   **Habit/Common Usage:** It's a common phrase in everyday speech, so it's easy to slip into using it.\n\n**Is it *wrong*?**\n\nNot necessarily *wrong*, but it's generally considered less formal and less precise. In formal writing or speaking, it's better to stick with just \"revert.\"\n\n**In conclusion:**\n\nWhile you'll hear \"revert back\" often (even on the BBC!), it's technically redundant. Using just \"revert\" is more concise and grammatically preferable, especially in formal contexts. If you're aiming for clarity and precision, avoid the \"back.\"\n",
